fork}}</ref>\n:\"[[Dangerous (David Guetta song)|Dangerous]]\" for [[David Guetta]]\n'''2015'''\n:\"[[Ghosttown (Madonna song)|Ghosttown]]\" for Madonna\n:\"[[Bitch I'm Madonna]]\" for Madonna feat. [[Nicki Minaj]]\n:\"RM486\" for [[Rose McGowan]] feat. Punishment\n:\"[[Could Have Been Me]]\" for [[The Struts]]\n'''2016'''\n:\"[[New Romantics (song)|New Romantics]]\" for [[Taylor Swift]]\n:\"[[Hold Up (song)|Hold Up]]\" for [[Beyonc\u00e9]]\n:\"\u00d3ve\u00f0ur\" for [[Sigur R\u00f3s]]\n:\"Make America Great Again\" for [[Pussy Riot]]\n:\"ManUNkind\" for [[Metallica]]\n'''2017'''\n:\"[[John Wayne (song)|John Wayne]]\" for [[Lady Gaga]]\n:\"[[Praying (song)|Praying]]\" for [[Kesha]]\n:\"[[The Way You Used to Do]]\" for [[Queens of the Stone Age]]\n:\"A Little Work\" for [[Fergie (singer)|Fergie]]\n:\"[[You're the Best Thing About Me]]\" for [[U2]]\n'''2018'''\n:\"Here Comes the Change\" for [[Kesha]]\n'''2019'''\n:\"[[God Control]]\" for Madonna\n:\"[[Under the Graveyard]]\" for [[Ozzy Osbourne]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Filmography==\n*''[[Spun]]'' (2002)\n*[[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]: ''[[I'm Going to Tell You a Secret]]'' (2005)\n*Madonna: ''[[The Confessions Tour (album)|Confessions Tour \u2013 Live from London]]'' (2006)\n*Madonna: ''[[The Confessions Tour (album)|The Confessions Tour]]'' (2007) - <small>(Won the 2008 [[Grammy Award for Best Music Film|Grammy Award for Best Long Form Music Video]])</small>\n*''[[Horsemen (film)|Horsemen]]'' (2009)<ref name=\"Metallum bio\">{{cite web|title=Jonas \u00c5kerlund Bio|url=http://www.metal-archives.com/artists/Jonas_%C3%85kerlund/742|publisher=Encyclopedia Metallum|accessdate=24 July 2012}}</ref>\n* ''[[Small Apartments]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[iTunes Live from Capitol Studios|Paul McCartney's Live Kisses]]'' (2012) - <small>(Won the 2014 [[Grammy Award for Best Music Film]])</small>\n* ''[[On the Run Tour: Beyonc\u00e9 and Jay-Z (TV program)|On the Run Tour: Beyonc\u00e9 and Jay Z]]'' (2014)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a595341/beyonce-and-jay-zs-on-the-run-tour-to-be-filmed-for-tv-special.html#~oQxn7FgO8oCOlS|title=Beyonc\u00c3\u00a9 and Jay Z tour for TV special|date=8 September 2014|work=Digital Spy}}</ref>\n* [[Taylor Swift]]: ''[[The 1989 World Tour#The 1989 World Tour Live|The 1989 World Tour Live]]'' (2015)\n* ''Roxette Diaries'' (2016)\n* ''[[Rammstein]]: Paris'' (2016)\n* ''[[Lords of Chaos (film)|Lords of Chaos]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Polar (film)|Polar]]'' (2019)\n\n==Books==\n* Henry Keazor, Thorsten W\u00fcbbena: ''[http://www.vttrs.de Video Thrills The Radio Star. Musikvideos: Geschichte, Themen, Analysen]''. [[Bielefeld]], Germany, 2005, p.&nbsp;117ss., p.&nbsp;146ss., p.&nbsp;448\n\n==Awards==\n\n*[[56th Annual Grammy Awards|2014]] \u2013 [[Grammy]] \u2013 [[Grammy Award for Best Music Film|Best Music Film]]: [[Paul McCartney]]'s ''\"Live Kisses\"''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicfilmweb.com/2014/01/paul-mccartney-nick-cave-grammys-sundance-music-documentary/|title=Awards Watch: Paul McCartney Takes Music Film Grammy, Nick Cave Doc a Double Winner at Sundance \u2013 MusicFilmWeb}}</ref>\n*2011 \u2013 [[Echo Awards]] \u2013 Best National Video: [[Rammstein]] ''\"[[Ich tu dir weh]]\"''\n*2010 \u2013 MVPA Awards \u2013 Best Collaboration: [[Lady Gaga]] feat [[Beyonc\u00e9]] ''\"[[Telephone (song)|Telephone]]\"'' \n*2009 \u2013 MVPA Awards \u2013 [[Lady Gaga]] ''\"[[Paparazzi (Lady Gaga)|Paparazzi]]\"''\n*2008 \u2013 MVPA Awards \u2013 [[James Blunt]] ''\"[[Same Mistake]]\"''\n*[[50th Annual Grammy Awards|2008]] \u2013 [[Grammy]] \u2013 [[Grammy Award for Best Music Video|Best Long Form Music Video]]: [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] NBC Special ''\"[[The Confessions Tour]]\"''\n*2008 \u2013 [[ADDY Awards|Silver Addy]] \u2013 [[Dell]] ''\"Work it Out\"''\n*2007 \u2013 MVPA Hall of Fame \u2013 [[The Prodigy|Prodigy]] ''\"[[Smack My Bitch Up]]\"''\n*2004 \u2013 MVPA Awards \u2013 [[Robbie Williams]] ''\"[[Come Undone (Robbie Williams song)|Come Undone]]\"''\n*[[41st Annual Grammy Awards|1999]] \u2013 [[Grammy]] \u2013 [[Grammy Award for Best Short Form Music Video|Best Short Form Music Video]]: [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] ''\"[[Ray of Light]]\"''\n*[[1998 MTV Video Music Awards|1998]] \u2013 [[MTV Video Music Award]] \u2013 [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] ''\"[[Ray of Light (song)|Ray of Light]]\"'' <small>(five awards: Video of the Year, Best Female Video, Best Director, Best Editing and Best Choreography - Jonas \u00c5kerlund was also the editor and he and Madonna were the choreographers for this video)</small>\n*[[1998 MTV Video Music Awards|1998]] \u2013 [[MTV Video Music Award]] \u2013 Best Dance Video: [[The Prodigy]] ''\"[[Smack My Bitch Up]]\"''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0959774}}\n*{{Sfdb name}}\n*[http://www.mvdbase.com/tech.php?last=Akerlund&first=Jonas/ Jonas \u00c5kerlund at the MVDbase.com]\n*[http://edition.cnn.com/2006/TRAVEL/10/11/stockholm.qa/ CNN interview with Jonas \u00c5kerlund]\n*[http://www.jonasakerlund.com/ Jonas \u00c5kerlund official web page]\n*[http://www.raf.se/ R.A.F. official web page]\n*{{cite web|last=Edwards|first=Gavin|title=Video Visionary Jonas \u00c5kerlund Pushes the Limits | url = https://www.wired.com/magazine/2011/05/pl_music_ackerlund/ | work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|accessdate=24 July 2012}}\n\n{{Jonas \u00c5kerlund}}\n{{Bathory (band)}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Akerlund, Jonas}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Black metal musicians]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Stockholm]]\n[[Category:Sommar (radio program) hosts]]\n[[Category:Swedish film directors]]\n[[Category:Swedish music video directors]]\n[[Category:Swedish heavy metal drummers]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eVideography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jonas_%C3%85kerlund"}
{"title_page": "Brian McGovern (judge)", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix = [[The Honorable|The Hon. Mr. Justice]]\n| name             = Brian McGovern\n| image            = \n| office           = Judge of the [[Court of Appeal (Ireland)|Court of Appeal]]\n| term_start       = 28 June 2018\n| term_end         = March 2020\n| nominator        = [[Government of the 32nd D\u00e1il|Government of Ireland]]\n| appointer        = [[Michael D. Higgins]]\n| office1          = Judge of the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]]\n| term_start1      = 11 March 2006\n| term_end1        = 25 June 2018\n| nominator1       = [[Government of the 29th D\u00e1il|Government of Ireland]]\n| appointer1       = [[Mary McAleese]]\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = \n| birth_place      = \n| death_date       =  \n| death_place      = \n| nationality      = [[Irish people|Irish]]\n| spouse           = \n| children         = \n| education        = [[Castleknock College]]\n| alma_mater       = {{Ubl|[[University College Dublin]]|[[King's Inns]]}}\n|}}\n'''Brian J. McGovern''' is a former Irish judge who served as a Judge of the [[Court of Appeal (Ireland)|Court of Appeal]] from June 2018 to March 2020. He previously served as a Judge of the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]] from 2007 to 2010.\n\n== Early life ==\nMcGovern attended [[Castleknock College]] and obtained a [[Bachelor of Civil Law|BCL]] from [[University College Dublin]] in 1971. He attended the [[King's Inns]] and was called to the [[Bar Council of Ireland|Bar]] in 1972. He became a senior counsel in 1991.<ref name=\"IT 2006\">{{cite news |title=High Court judge is nominated |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/inshort-1.997712 |accessdate=16 May 2019 |work=The Irish Times |date=3 May 2006}}</ref> During his career as a barrister he frequently practiced in areas of both criminal and civil law. He served as President of the Irish Maritime Law Association.<ref name=\"IT 2006\" /> He represented [[Total S.A.]] in an inquiry into the [[Whiddy Island disaster]].<ref>{{cite news |title=New judge for High Court |url=https://www.breakingnews.ie/ireland/new-judge-for-high-court-256901.html |accessdate=16 May 2019 |work=BreakingNews.ie |date=2 May 2006}}</ref>\n\n== Judicial career ==\n=== High Court ===\nHe was appointed to the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]] in 2006.<ref name=\"IT 2006\" /> Soon after his appointment he heard a case regarding the right of access of a woman to frozen embryos against the wishes of her husband.<ref name=\"Examiner Retire\" /> He acted as the designated [[arbitration]] judge for Ireland until his appointment to the Court of Appeal.<ref>{{cite news |title=800 secondary teachers to train in dispute resolution |url=https://www.lawsociety.ie/gazette/Top-Stories/800-secondary-teachers-to-be-trained-in-mediation-and-dispute-resolution/ |accessdate=16 May 2019 |work=Law Society Gazette |date=19 November 2018}}</ref> He was also the presiding judge in the specialist Commercial Court.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ireland\u2019s Designated Arbitration Judge |url=https://www.arbitrationireland.com/irelands-designated-arbitration-judge/ |website=Arbitration Ireland |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref> In the Commercial Court, he was the trial judge for high-profile disputes involving [[Rory McIlroy]], [[Gay Byrne]] and [[Mick Wallace]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Judge in Rory McIlroy case against former management company orders peace talks |url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/courts/judge-in-rory-mcilroy-case-against-former-management-company-orders-peace-talks-30591119.html |accessdate=16 May 2019 |work=Irish Independent |date=16 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Faolain |first1=Aodhan |title=Gay Byrne and family settle \u20ac1.2m financial dispute |url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/courts/gay-byrne-and-family-settle-1-2m-financial-dispute-36561792.html |accessdate=16 May 2019 |work=Irish Independent |date=2 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=High Court grants judgment for \u20ac2m against Mick Wallace |url=https://www.rte.ie/news/2016/0129/763857-mick-wallace-judgement/ |accessdate=16 May 2019 |work=RT\u00c9 News |date=29 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Court of Appeal ===\nMcGovern was appointed to the Court of Appeal in June 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=President appoints new Judges |url=https://president.ie/en/diary/details/president-appoints-ms-justice-marie-baker-and-mr-justice-brian-j.-mcgovern |publisher=President.ie |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref> He retired as a judge in March 2020. He will serve on a statutory tribunal into matters arising from the [[2018 CervicalCheck cancer scandal]] with [[Mary Irvine]] and [[Michael Peart (judge)|Michael Peart]].<ref name=\"Examiner Retire\">{{cite news |title=Tributes paid to Justice Brian McGovern on his final day on the bench |url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/tributes-paid-to-justice-brian-mcgovern-on-his-final-day-on-the-bench-987573.html |accessdate=12 March 2020 |work=www.irishexaminer.com |date=12 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McGovern, Brian}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Judges of the Court of Appeal (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:High Court judges (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:People educated at Castleknock College]]\n[[Category:21st-century Irish judges]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish lawyers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's Inns]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix = [[The Honorable|The Hon. Mr. Justice]]\n| name             = Brian McGovern\n| image            = \n| office           = Judge of the [[Court of Appeal (Ireland)|Court of Appeal]]\n| term_start       = 28 June 2018\n| term_end         = March 2020\n| nominator        = [[Government of the 32nd D\u00e1il|Government of Ireland]]\n| appointer        = [[Michael D. Higgins]]\n| office1          = Judge of the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]]\n| term_start1      = 11 March 2006\n| term_end1        = 25 June 2018\n| nominator1       = [[Government of the 29th D\u00e1il|Government of Ireland]]\n| appointer1       = [[Mary McAleese]]\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = \n| birth_place      = \n| death_date       =  \n| death_place      = \n| nationality      = [[Irish people|Irish]]\n| spouse           = \n| children         = \n| education        = [[Castleknock College]]\n| alma_mater       = {{Ubl|[[University College Dublin]]|[[King's Inns]]}}\n|}}\n'''Brian J. McGovern''' is a former Irish judge who served as a Judge of the [[Court of Appeal (Ireland)|Court of Appeal]] from June 2018 to March 2020. He previously served as a Judge of the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]] from 2007 to 2010.\n\n== Early life ==\nMcGovern attended [[Castleknock College]] and obtained a [[Bachelor of Civil Law|BCL]] from [[University College Dublin]] in 1971. He attended the [[King's Inns]] and was called to the [[Bar Council of Ireland|Bar]] in 1972. He became a senior counsel in 1991.<ref name=\"IT 2006\">{{cite news |title=High Court judge is nominated |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/inshort-1.997712 |accessdate=16 May 2019 |work=The Irish Times |date=3 May 2006}}</ref> During his career as a barrister he frequently practiced in areas of both criminal and civil law. He served as President of the Irish Maritime Law Association.<ref name=\"IT 2006\" /> He represented [[Total S.A.]] in an inquiry into the [[Whiddy Island disaster]].<ref>{{cite news |title=New judge for High Court |url=https://www.breakingnews.ie/ireland/new-judge-for-high-court-256901.html |accessdate=16 May 2019 |work=BreakingNews.ie |date=2 May 2006}}</ref>\n\n== Judicial career ==\n=== High Court ===\nHe was appointed to the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]] in 2006.<ref name=\"IT 2006\" /> Soon after his appointment he heard a case regarding the right of access of a woman to frozen embryos against the wishes of her husband.<ref name=\"Examiner Retire\" /> He acted as the designated [[arbitration]] judge for Ireland until his appointment to the Court of Appeal.<ref>{{cite news |title=800 secondary teachers to train in dispute resolution |url=https://www.lawsociety.ie/gazette/Top-Stories/800-secondary-teachers-to-be-trained-in-mediation-and-dispute-resolution/ |accessdate=16 May 2019 |work=Law Society Gazette |date=19 November 2018}}</ref> He was also the presiding judge in the specialist Commercial Court.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ireland\u2019s Designated Arbitration Judge |url=https://www.arbitrationireland.com/irelands-designated-arbitration-judge/ |website=Arbitration Ireland |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref> In the Commercial Court, he was the trial judge for high-profile disputes involving [[Rory McIlroy]], [[Gay Byrne]] and [[Mick Wallace]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Judge in Rory McIlroy case against former management company orders peace talks |url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/courts/judge-in-rory-mcilroy-case-against-former-management-company-orders-peace-talks-30591119.html |accessdate=16 May 2019 |work=Irish Independent |date=16 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Faolain |first1=Aodhan |title=Gay Byrne and family settle \u20ac1.2m financial dispute |url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/courts/gay-byrne-and-family-settle-1-2m-financial-dispute-36561792.html |accessdate=16 May 2019 |work=Irish Independent |date=2 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=High Court grants judgment for \u20ac2m against Mick Wallace |url=https://www.rte.ie/news/2016/0129/763857-mick-wallace-judgement/ |accessdate=16 May 2019 |work=RT\u00c9 News |date=29 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Court of Appeal ===\nMcGovern was appointed to the Court of Appeal in June 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=President appoints new Judges |url=https://president.ie/en/diary/details/president-appoints-ms-justice-marie-baker-and-mr-justice-brian-j.-mcgovern |publisher=President.ie |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref> He retired as a judge in March 2020. He will serve on a statutory tribunal into matters arising from the [[2018 CervicalCheck cancer controversy]] with [[Mary Irvine]] and [[Michael Peart (judge)|Michael Peart]].<ref name=\"Examiner Retire\">{{cite news |title=Tributes paid to Justice Brian McGovern on his final day on the bench |url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/tributes-paid-to-justice-brian-mcgovern-on-his-final-day-on-the-bench-987573.html |accessdate=12 March 2020 |work=www.irishexaminer.com |date=12 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McGovern, Brian}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Judges of the Court of Appeal (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:High Court judges (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:People educated at Castleknock College]]\n[[Category:21st-century Irish judges]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish lawyers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's Inns]]\n", "name_user": "Bygmester", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brian_McGovern_(judge)"}
{"title_page": "Canadian Journalism Foundation", "text_new": "The '''Canadian Journalism Foundation (CJF)''' is a [[non-profit]] organization that was founded in 1990 and promotes [[Canada|Canadian]] [[journalism]] by celebrating journalistic achievement through an annual awards program; by operating journalism websites, J-Source.ca (English) and ProjetJ.ca (French), in cooperation with the country's journalism schools; by organizing events that facilitate dialogue among journalists, business people, government officials, academics and students about the role of the media in Canadian society; and by fostering opportunities for journalism education, training and research.\n\nThe Foundation's [[award]]s program recognizes and encourages excellence in journalism and provides unique professional development opportunities for Canadian journalists. The Excellence in Journalism Award is presented to a journalistic organization for exceptional performance. The Lifetime Achievement Award recognizes an individual who has made an outstanding lifetime contribution to journalism in Canada. The Canadian Journalism Fellowships, awarded by [[Massey College]] in the [[University of Toronto]], offer mid-career journalists an opportunity to reevaluate and refresh their careers in an exciting academic atmosphere. The [[Greg Clark (journalist)|Greg Clark]] Award is designed to offer working journalists early in their career a chance to gain insight, strategic information and meet key decision-makers in a sector or issue they regularly cover.\n\nThe Foundation's public programs, in the form of panel discussions and other events, are targeted at journalists, media executives, as well as academic and business leaders to help illuminate current issues or concerns.\n\nThe Canadian Journalism Foundation also manages the [[Canadian Journalism Project]] and its website, '''J-Source''', in collaboration with leading journalism schools and organizations.\n\nIn 2018, the CJF started celebrating World News Day, encouraging news outlets around the world to communicate to the public the role of professional journalism plays in democracies. WND is held annually in May in many countries, although several Asian news outlets choose to celebrate it on September 28<sup>th</sup>, which correspond with [[UNESCO]]\u2019s International Day for Universal Access to Information.{{R|MT}}\n\nDuring the 2019 Canadian federal election, the Foundation launched a news literary campaign called NewsWise. Using humour and Canadian media personalities, the initiative offers the public tools to check the accuracy of the information they copme across while using the internet and social media. The campaign is funded by a contribution from Google of Can$1 million.{{R|CP}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.cjf-fjc.ca/ Canadian Journalism Foundation website]\n* [https://doubtit.ca/ The CJF's news literacy program]\n* [https://doubtit.ca/ The CJF's news literacy program]\n\n\n\n{{journalism-stub}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=CP>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nationalnewswatch.com/2019/10/02/journalism-group-launches-anti-fake-news-campaign-ahead-of-election/#.XZSxNEZPHIW|title=Journalism group launches anti-fake news campaign ahead of election|last=Farooqui|first=Salmaan|date=2019-10-02|work=Canadian Press|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=MT>{{Cite news|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2019/09/26/world-news-day-to-celebrate-journalism/|title=World News Day to celebrate journalism|last=Rekhi|first=Shefali|date=2019-09-26|work=Manila Times|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:Canadian journalism organizations]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1990]]\n[[Category:1990 establishments in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{unreferenced|date=July 2011}}\n\n{{Infobox organization\n| name                = Canadian Journalism Foundation\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| logo                = \n| logo_size           = \n| logo_alt            = \n| logo_caption        = \n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| map                 = \n| map_size            = \n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = \n| map2                = \n| map2_size           = \n| map2_alt            = \n| map2_caption        = \n| abbreviation        = CJF\n| nickname            = \n| pronounce           = \n| pronounce ref       = \n| pronounce comment   = \n| pronounce 2         = \n| named_after         = \n| motto               = As journalism goes, so does democracy\n| predecessor         = \n| merged              = \n| successor           = \n| formation           = 1990\n| founder             = F.L.R. (Eric) Jackman\n| founding_location   = \n| extinction          = <!-- use {{end date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| merger              = \n| type                = \n| tax_id              = <!-- or | vat_id = (for European organizations) -->\n| registration_id     = <!-- for non-profit org -->\n| status              = \n| purpose             = Celebrate and facilitate excellence in journalism\n| professional_title  = \n| headquarters        = Toronto\n| location            = \n| location2           = \n| additional_location = \n| additional_location2= \n| coordinates         = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|display=inline, title}} -->\n| origins             = \n| region              = \n| products            = \n| services            = Media literacy campign, fellowship program, speakers series\n| methods             = \n| fields              = Journalism\n| membership          = \n| membership_year     = \n| language            = English, French\n| owner               = <!-- or | owners = -->\n| sec_gen             = <!-- or | gen_sec for General Secretary -->\n| leader_title        = Chair of the board\n| leader_name         = David Walmsley\n| leader_title2       = President and Executive Director\n| leader_name2        = Natalie Turvey\n| leader_title3       = \n| leader_name3        = \n| leader_title4       = \n| leader_name4        = \n| board_of_directors  = \n| key_people          = \n| main_organ          = \n| parent_organization = \n| subsidiaries        = \n| secessions          = \n| affiliations        = \n| budget              = \n| budget_year         = \n| revenue             = \n| revenue_year        = \n| disbursements       = \n| expenses            = \n| expenses_year       = \n| endowment           = \n| endowment_year      = \n| staff               = 3\n| staff_year          = 2019\n| volunteers          = \n| volunteers_year     = \n| students            = \n| students_year       = \n| website             = [http://cjf-fjc.ca cjf-fjc.ca]\n| remarks             = \n| formerly            = \n| footnotes           = \n| bodystyle           = \n}}\n\nFounded in 1990, The '''Canadian Journalism Foundation (CJF)''' is a [[non-profit]] organization that promotes [[Canada|Canadian]] [[journalism]] by celebrating journalistic achievement through an annual awards program; by operating journalism websites, J-Source.ca (English) and ProjetJ.ca (French), in cooperation with the country's journalism schools; by organizing events that facilitate dialogue among journalists, business people, government officials, academics and students about the role of the media in Canadian society; and by fostering opportunities for journalism education, training and research.\n\nThe Foundation's [[award]]s program recognizes and encourages excellence in journalism and provides unique professional development opportunities for Canadian journalists. The Excellence in Journalism Award is presented to a journalistic organization for exceptional performance. The Lifetime Achievement Award recognizes an individual who has made an outstanding lifetime contribution to journalism in Canada. The Canadian Journalism Fellowships, awarded by [[Massey College]] in the [[University of Toronto]], offer mid-career journalists an opportunity to reevaluate and refresh their careers in an exciting academic atmosphere. The [[Greg Clark (journalist)|Greg Clark]] Award is designed to offer working journalists early in their career a chance to gain insight, strategic information and meet key decision-makers in a sector or issue they regularly cover.\n\nThe Foundation's public programs, in the form of panel discussions and other events, are targeted at journalists, media executives, as well as academic and business leaders to help illuminate current issues or concerns.\n\nThe Canadian Journalism Foundation also manages the [[Canadian Journalism Project]] and its website, '''J-Source''', in collaboration with leading journalism schools and organizations.\n\nIn 2018, the CJF started celebrating World News Day, encouraging news outlets around the world to communicate to the public the role of professional journalism plays in democracies. WND is held annually in May in many countries, although several Asian news outlets choose to celebrate it on September 28<sup>th</sup>, which correspond with [[UNESCO]]\u2019s International Day for Universal Access to Information.{{R|MT}}\n\nDuring the 2019 Canadian federal election, the Foundation launched a news literary campaign called NewsWise. Using humour and Canadian media personalities, the initiative offers the public tools to check the accuracy of the information they copme across while using the internet and social media. The campaign is funded by a contribution from Google of Can$1 million.{{R|CP}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.cjf-fjc.ca/ Canadian Journalism Foundation website]\n* [https://doubtit.ca/ The CJF's news literacy program]\n* [https://doubtit.ca/ The CJF's news literacy program]\n\n\n\n{{journalism-stub}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=CP>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nationalnewswatch.com/2019/10/02/journalism-group-launches-anti-fake-news-campaign-ahead-of-election/#.XZSxNEZPHIW|title=Journalism group launches anti-fake news campaign ahead of election|last=Farooqui|first=Salmaan|date=2019-10-02|work=Canadian Press|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=MT>{{Cite news|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2019/09/26/world-news-day-to-celebrate-journalism/|title=World News Day to celebrate journalism|last=Rekhi|first=Shefali|date=2019-09-26|work=Manila Times|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:Canadian journalism organizations]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1990]]\n[[Category:1990 establishments in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "Pittstone", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canadian_Journalism_Foundation"}
{"title_page": "Ghimbav", "text_new": "{{for|the river in Arge\u0219 County|Ghimbav (river)}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = town\n|county                 = Bra\u0219ov\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption = Location in Bra\u0219ov County\n|official_name=Ghimbav\n|image_shield=ROU BV Ghimbav CoA.jpg\n|image_map=Ghimbav jud Brasov.jpg\n|leader_name= Dorel Toma<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.2016bec.ro/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/SIAL2016_P_Lista_Moc-2.xlsx |title=Results of the 2016 local elections |publisher=Central Electoral Bureau |accessdate=2020-04-03 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|leader_party=PSD\n|area_total_km2=28.08\n|coordinates              = {{coord|45|39|46|N|25|30|22|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|website={{url|http://www.primaria-ghimbav.ro}}\n}}\n[[File:Ghimbav2.JPG|thumb|left|Center of Ghimbav. One can see the top of the local [[Villages with fortified churches in Transylvania|fortified church]]'s tower on the right.]]\n'''Ghimbav''' ({{lang-de|Weidenbach}}; {{lang-hu|Vidomb\u00e1k}}) is a town in [[Bra\u0219ov County]], [[Transylvania]], central [[Romania]]. It is located in the centre of Romania, 5 miles (8 km) west of [[Bra\u0219ov]].\n\n==History==\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Census data\n|2002 |5112\n|2011 |4698\n}}\n\nThe town was first mentioned in a letter written in 1420 by [[King of Hungary|King]] [[Sigismund of Luxembourg|Sigismund]] of [[Hungary]]. He advised the inhabitants of Weidenbach/Ghimbav to join their forces together with the people living in three other neighboring Saxon villages (Petersberg/[[S\u00e2npetru]], Honigberg/[[H\u0103rman]] and Brenndorf/[[Bod, Bra\u0219ov|Bod]]) and contribute to the construction of the stone fortress of [[Bra\u0219ov]]. \n\nThe Ottomans invaded Ghimbav in 1422. In 1469 a major fire damaged the town. In 1611 the Hungarian prince [[Gabriel B\u00e1thory]] set fire to several villages in [[Burzenland]] (\u0162ara B\u00e2rsei); Ghimbav was one of them. \n\nThe local church and the bell tower were built around 1300. In the 15th century a fortress was built around the church. It was hit by lightning in 1642 and suffered major damages. In 1666 the city hall was moved inside the fortress as well as several other houses. These houses were demolished in 1940. The defensive walls were partially ruined in the 20th century.\n\n==Industry==\n[[Industria Aeronautic\u0103 Rom\u00e2n\u0103|IAR]], a Romanian builder of helicopters and small planes, is located in Ghimbav. Among other aircraft, it builds the [[Eurocopter]]/IAR Puma military transport helicopter.\n\n[[Premium AEROTEC]], a subsidiary of [[EADS]], has also built a factory in Ghimbav.\n\n{{commons category|Ghimbav}}\n\n{{Bra\u015fov County}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Romania]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Bra\u0219ov County]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the river in Arge\u0219 County|Ghimbav (river)}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = town\n|county                 = Bra\u0219ov\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption = Location in Bra\u0219ov County\n|official_name=Ghimbav\n|image_shield=ROU BV Ghimbav CoA.jpg\n|image_map=Ghimbav jud Brasov.jpg\n|leader_name=Toma Dorel\n|leader_party=PSD\n|area_total_km2=28.08\n|coordinates              = {{coord|45|39|46|N|25|30|22|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|website={{url|http://www.primaria-ghimbav.ro}}\n}}\n[[File:Ghimbav2.JPG|thumb|left|Center of Ghimbav. One can see the top of the local [[Villages with fortified churches in Transylvania|fortified church]]'s tower on the right.]]\n'''Ghimbav''' ({{lang-de|Weidenbach}}; {{lang-hu|Vidomb\u00e1k}}) is a town in [[Bra\u0219ov County]], [[Transylvania]], central [[Romania]]. It is located in the centre of Romania, 5 miles (8 km) west of [[Bra\u0219ov]].\n\n==History==\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Census data\n|2002 |5112\n|2011 |4698\n}}\n\nThe town was first mentioned in a letter written in 1420 by [[King of Hungary|King]] [[Sigismund of Luxembourg|Sigismund]] of [[Hungary]]. He advised the inhabitants of Weidenbach/Ghimbav to join their forces together with the people living in three other neighboring Saxon villages (Petersberg/[[S\u00e2npetru]], Honigberg/[[H\u0103rman]] and Brenndorf/[[Bod, Bra\u0219ov|Bod]]) and contribute to the construction of the stone fortress of [[Bra\u0219ov]]. \n\nThe Ottomans invaded Ghimbav in 1422. In 1469 a major fire damaged the town. In 1611 the Hungarian prince [[Gabriel B\u00e1thory]] set fire to several villages in [[Burzenland]] (\u0162ara B\u00e2rsei); Ghimbav was one of them. \n\nThe local church and the bell tower were built around 1300. In the 15th century a fortress was built around the church. It was hit by lightning in 1642 and suffered major damages. In 1666 the city hall was moved inside the fortress as well as several other houses. These houses were demolished in 1940. The defensive walls were partially ruined in the 20th century.\n\n==Industry==\n[[Industria Aeronautic\u0103 Rom\u00e2n\u0103|IAR]], a Romanian builder of helicopters and small planes, is located in Ghimbav. Among other aircraft, it builds the [[Eurocopter]]/IAR Puma military transport helicopter.\n\n[[Premium AEROTEC]], a subsidiary of [[EADS]], has also built a factory in Ghimbav.\n\n{{commons category|Ghimbav}}\n\n{{Bra\u015fov County}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Romania]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Bra\u0219ov County]]\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ghimbav"}
{"title_page": "Jack Pope", "text_new": "{{Short description|American judge}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|image=Jack Pope in home library, 2011 (cropped).jpg\n|caption= Retired Texas Chief Justice Jack Pope, aged 97, in his home library, March 2011\n|order=\n|office= [[Texas Supreme Court#Chief Justice, Place 1|23rd Texas Supreme Court Justice, <br/> Chief Justice]]\n|term_start=November 29, 1982\n|term_end= January 4, 1985\n|predecessor=[[Joe R. Greenhill]]\n|successor=[[John Hill (Texas politician)|John Hill]]\n|order2=\n|office2=[[Texas Supreme Court]] Associate Justice, Place 2\n|term_start2=January 4, 1965\n|term_end2=November 29, 1982\n|order3=\n|office3=4th Court of Civil Appeals, Justice\n|term_start3=September 12, 1951\n|term_end3=1964\n|order4=\n|office4=94th District Court, District Judge\n|term_start4= December 16, 1946\n|term_end4=1951\n|party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|birth_name=Andrew Jackson Pope Jr.\n|birth_date={{birth date|1913|4|18}}\n|birth_place=[[Abilene, Texas]], U.S.\n|death_date={{death date and age|2017|2|25|1913|4|18}}\n|death_place=[[Austin, Texas]], U.S.\n|resting_place=[[Texas State Cemetery]] <br/> [[Austin, Texas]]\n|spouse=Allene Nichols (d.2004)\n|children=Andrew Jackson Pope III <br/>Walter Allen Pope\n|religion=[[Churches of Christ]]\n|alma_mater=[[University of Texas School of Law]]<br/>[[Abilene Christian University]]\n|profession=[[Lawyer]]\n|allegiance={{flag|United States}}\n|branch={{flag|United States Navy|23px}} <br/> [[United States Naval Reserve]]\n|serviceyears=1944\u20131946\n|battles=[[World War II]]\n}}\n\n''' Jack Pope, also known as, Mr. Meth Head is so annoying and likes to watch logan and jake paul..\n\nPope holds the record of the longest sitting justice in Texas Supreme Court history, having served for 38 years.<ref name= \"Lawbook\" /> At the time of his [[centenarian|100th birthday]], he was the oldest living former Chief Justice of any supreme court in the United States, as well as the longest living chief justice of any supreme court of any state in [[United States]] history.<ref name= \"Lawbook\" >{{cite web |url= http://www.supreme.courts.state.tx.us/pdf/Jackpope100Reprint.pdf |title= Chief Justice Pope Turns 100 |date= April 18, 2013 |work= The Texas Lawbook |publisher= The Supreme Court of Texas |accessdate= May 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nPope was born in [[Abilene, Texas]] <ref name= \"HouseRes\"/> to Dr. Andrew Jackson Pope Sr., a physician, and Ruth Adelia Taylor, a native of [[Nebraska]].<ref name=\"UTBio\">{{cite web |url= http://www.laits.utexas.edu/txp_media/html/just/justices/14.html |title= Pope, Andrew J. | year=2006 | publisher= The University of Texas at Austin|accessdate= July 2, 2013}}</ref> He is a descendant of Andrew Jackson Berry, who fought at the [[Battle of San Jacinto]] in the [[Texas Revolution]].<ref name= \"AltoHerald\"/> After completing high school in Abilene in 1930,<ref name= \"HouseRes\" /> he earned a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree<ref name= \"HouseRes\"/> from Abilene Christian College (now [[Abilene Christian University]])<ref name= \"HouseRes\" /> in 1934, where he had served as Students' Association President.<ref name=\"ACU Today\"/> Pope then served as a student editor of the ''[[Texas Law Review]]'' at the [[University of Texas School of Law]], graduating with a [[Bachelor of Laws]] degree and in 1937 was licensed by the bar.<ref name= \"HouseRes\" /> In 1938, he married Allene Nichols, an elementary school teacher and graduate of the University of Texas whom he met while attending law school;<ref name=\"UTBio\"/> the couple had two sons.<ref name=\"AlleneObit\">{{cite web |url= http://www.christianchronicle.org/article1850458~Obituary%3A_Allene_Nichols_Pope |title= Obituary: Allene Nichols Pope |date=May 2004 |publisher= Christian Chronicle |accessdate= July 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Early legal career ===\nAfter obtaining his license to practice law in Texas in 1937,<ref name= \"HouseRes\"/> Pope \"joined his uncle, former state representative [[Walter Elmer Pope|Walter E. Pope]],\"<ref name= \"HouseRes\"/> at his law firm in [[Corpus Christi, Texas|Corpus Christi]].<ref name= \"HouseRes\"/> His practice consisted of both civil and criminal matters,<ref name= \"HouseRes\"/> such as creditors' rights, oil and gas, personal injury, and family law.<ref name=\"UTBio\"/>\n\nHe went on to manage his uncle's business, the Highway Transportation Company, a passenger \"bus line which operated between Houston, Corpus Christi, and San Antonio.\"<ref name=\"AltoHerald\"/> During this time, he was engaged in the legal interpretation of the new transportation regulatory laws, as well as [[New Deal]] labor laws.<ref name= \"HouseRes\" >{{cite web |url= ftp://ftp.legis.state.tx.us/bills/83R/billtext/html/house_resolutions/HR00800_HR00899/HR00891I.htm |title= House Resolution No. 891 |year= 2013 |publisher= Texas House of Representatives |location= Austin, Texas |accessdate= May 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\nWhen the United States entered [[World War II]], Pope joined the [[United States Navy Reserve|Naval Reserve]] in 1944.<ref name= \"HouseRes\" /> He served on the legal staff of the [[Naval Air Station Corpus Christi|Naval Air Training Station]] in [[Corpus Christi, Texas|Corpus Christi]], as well as on stations in [[Washington, D.C.]] and [[Naval Air Station North Island|San Diego]],<ref name=\"UTBio\"/> until his discharge in 1946.<ref name= \"HouseRes\" />\n\n=== Judge and legal scholar ===\n\n==== District Judge ====\nIn late 1946 Pope was appointed by [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[governor of Texas|Governor]] [[Coke R. Stevenson]] to fill the unexpired term of Judge Allen Wood of the 94th District Court.<ref name=\"AltoHerald\">{{cite web |url= http://texashistory.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metapth215807/m1/3/?q=jack pope | title= Judge Jack Pope Announces for Supreme Court |date=December 1963 |publisher= The Alto Herald|location= Alto, Texas |accessdate= July 1, 2013}}</ref> \nGovernor Stevenson's successor, [[Beauford H. Jester]], then appointed Pope to Judge Wood's four-year term, which began January 1, 1947.<ref name=\"UTBio\"/>\n\nHe became Texas' youngest district judge at the time when he sat on the bench at 33 years of age.<ref name= \"HouseRes\" /> During his time on the district court bench, Pope began writing for and lecturing at legal institutes and before bar associations across [[South Texas]]. His concerns included legal ethics, trial administration, best practices for presenting and excluding evidence, and the Texas [[Jury trial|jury system]]. On several occasions he was appointed to other regional courts to assist when another judge was recused from presiding.<ref name=\"UTBio\"/>\n\n==== Court of Appeals Justice ====\nIn 1950 the Nueces County [[Bar association|Bar Association]] prepared a resolution urging him to campaign for the [[Texas Courts of Appeals|4th Court of Civil Appeals]] in [[San Antonio, Texas|San Antonio]].<ref name=\"UTBio\"/>  Since 1892, of the fifteen judges who had served on that court, all but five had come from San Antonio.<ref name=\"UTBio\"/>  The legal community of [[Nueces County, Texas|Nueces County]] and the [[Rio Grande Valley]] counties hoped to change that trend by nominating and actively campaigning for the young judge.,<ref name=\"UTBio\"/><ref name=\"ACU Today\"/> After winning the primary in July, Pope was appointed to the 4th Court of Appeals' bench by Governor [[Allan Shivers]] to replace Justice Lorenz Broeter, who had resigned.<ref name=\"UTBio\"/>  Pope sat on the court until 1950, whereupon he began serving his own six-year term, with voters subsequently re-electing him to an additional two terms, for a total of 14 years.,<ref name=\"UTBio\"/><ref name=AltoHerald/> In 1961 Pope's judicial review of water rights derived from Spanish and Mexican [[land grant]]s <ref name= \"Lawbook\" /> in the case ''State v. Valmont Plantations'' set a legal precedent which would thereafter set the standard for the adjudication of Texas [[Water law in the United States|water law]].<ref name= \"HouseRes\" /><ref name=\"UTBio\"/><ref name=\"Water Law\">{{cite web |url= http://www.tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/gyw01 | author=Otis W. Templer | title= Water Law |publisher= Texas State Historical Association |accessdate= July 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==== Supreme Court Justice ====\nIn December 1963, Pope declared his intention to run for a vacancy position on the Texas Supreme Court, after receiving 80 petitions from 55 Texas counties with over 2,000 signatures of attorneys pledging their support,<ref name=AltoHerald/> and in 1964 he was elected an [[Associate Justice|associate justice]].<ref name= \"HouseRes\" /> During his tenure as an associate justice, he spearheaded an initiative with the [[State Bar of Texas]] to institute a program for continuing statewide judicial education, and to develop judicial ethics rules. His efforts resulted in both compulsory continuing judicial education and the Court's adoption of The Texas Code of Judicial Conduct in 1974.<ref name= \"Ethicist\" >{{cite web |url= http://www.legalethicstexas.com/Spotlight-on-Ethics/The-Ethicists/Justice-Jack-Pope.aspx |title= Chief Justice Jack Pope |year= 2013 |publisher= Texas Center for Legal Ethics |accessdate= May 14, 2013}}</ref> He was also directly involved in the creation of the Texas State Law Library in 1971, and served on the Friends of the State Law Library Board of Directors.<ref name= \"HouseRes\" />\n\n==== Supreme Court Chief Justice ====\nWhen [[Joe R. Greenhill]] resigned as Chief Justice in October 1982, Governor [[William P. Clements]] appointed Pope to succeed Greenhill.<ref name=\"RioGrande Herald\">{{cite web |url= http://texashistory.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metapth194903/m1/11/?q=jack pope |title= Pope Sworn In |date=23 December 1982 |publisher= The Rio Grande Herald |location= Rio Grande City, Texas | accessdate= July 1, 2013}}</ref> As a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], Clements had crossed party lines to appoint Pope, a lifelong Democrat.<ref name=\"Optimist2\">{{cite web |url= http://texashistory.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metapth96041 |title= Senate Announces Delay in Confirming Justice Pope |date=28 January 1983 |publisher= The Optimist |location= Abilene, Texas | accessdate= July 2, 2013}}</ref> However, when Democrat [[Mark White]] was elected governor that November, a group of 14 Democratic legislators in the Texas Senate publicly stated that they would \"bust\"<ref name=\"Optimist2\"/> all lame-duck appointments by the outgoing Republican governor<ref name=\"RioGrande Herald\"/> regardless of qualifications.<ref name=\"Optimist2\"/><ref name=\"Optimist\">{{cite web |url= http://texashistory.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metapth96043/m1/11/?q=\"chief justice\" pope |title= Jack Pope confirmed Chief Justice |date=4 February 1983 |publisher= The Optimist |location= Abilene, Texas | accessdate= July 2, 2013}}</ref> The Democratic senators attempted to negotiate terms to keep true to their statement of blocking all of the Republican's appointments, while also preserving the power of the Chief Justice position for the Democratic party.<ref name= \"Own Man\"/> However, Pope refused to promise a retirement or interim-only judgeship, saying: \"The citizens of Texas do not want their Chief Justice, or any judge, to make a deal to get a job. If he'll make a deal to get a job, he may keep on making deals to keep that job.\"<ref name= \"Own Man\"/> At a news conference in early 1983, Governor White stated that he did not oppose Pope's confirmation; and in February the Senate voted 29\u20132 in approval.<ref name=\"Optimist2\"/><ref name=\"Optimist\"/>\n\nAfter federal cuts to legal-assistance financing in the early 1980s, as Chief Justice he advocated a way for Texas to guarantee income to finance legal assistance for the poor by using pooled trust-account interest. This program, known as [[Interest on Lawyer Trust Accounts]] (IOLTA), is now used in every U.S. state.<ref name=\"LegalAid\">{{cite web |url= http://www.supreme.courts.state.tx.us/pdf/Governorsignslegalaidsupport.pdf |title= House Bill 1445, Raising Attorney General's Contributions to Civil Legal Services, Signed by Governor Perry |date=May 2013 |publisher= Texas Supreme Court |location= Austin, Texas |accessdate= May 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Later life and death ==\n\nUpon his 1985 retirement Pope had written over 700 opinions for the Supreme Court,<ref name=\"Own Man\">{{cite web |url= http://law.duke.edu/sites/default/files/news/hecht2.pdf |title= Supreme Court of Texas Chief Justice Andrew Jackson \"Jack\" Pope, Jr.: \"Always His Own Man\" |author= Hecht, Nathan |authorlink= Nathan Hecht |date=October 2012 |work= The Storied Third Branch |publisher= Center of Judicial Studies |location= [[Duke University School of Law]] |accessdate= May 14, 2013}}</ref> with an additional 500 opinions as a district judge and court of appeals justice.<ref name=\"AltoHerald\"/> Although he had served as a judge for over 38 years, 21 of those years on the Texas Supreme Court, nearing the Court's mandatory retirement age in 1985 Chief Justice Pope wryly commented: \"Just about the time I was getting the hang of being a judge, I had to retire.\"<ref name=\"UTBio\"/><ref name=\"ACU Today\">{{cite web |url= http://blogs.acu.edu/acutoday/2010/10/05/jack-pope-honored-by-texas-bar-association/ |title= Jack Pope honored for lifetime achievements |year= 2010 |work= blogs.acu.edu |publisher= Abilene Christian University |accessdate= July 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1989 [[Abilene Christian University]] established the Jack Pope Fellows Program \"to offer scholarships to ACU students pursuing public service careers.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.acuoptimist.com/2010/09/hailey-honored-with-endowment-fund/ |title= Hailey honored with endowment fund |author= Williamson, Kelsi |date= September 7, 2010 |work= The Optimist |publisher= Abilene Christian University |access-date= May 14, 2013 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20151121054435/http://www.acuoptimist.com/2010/09/hailey-honored-with-endowment-fund/ |archive-date= November 21, 2015 |df=  }}</ref> The interdisciplinary program gives students with \"good minds and character\" public service educational opportunities in and out of the classroom.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.acu.edu/academics/cas/politicalscience/jackpopefellows/index.html |title= Jack Pope Fellows Program |year= 2013 |work= acu.edu |publisher= Abilene Christian University |accessdate= May 14, 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130403091226/http://www.acu.edu/academics/cas/politicalscience/jackpopefellows/index.html |archive-date= April 3, 2013 |url-status= dead }}</ref> Also in 1989, Pope co-founded the non-profit Texas Center for Legal Ethics with other former Chief Justices [[Joe R. Greenhill]] and [[Robert W. Calvert]].<ref name=TCLE>{{cite web |url= http://www.legalethicstexas.com/spotlight-on-ethics/awards/pope-award.aspx |title= Chief Justice Jack Pope Professionalism Award |year= 2013 |publisher= Texas Center for Legal Ethics |accessdate= May 14, 2013}}</ref> Its mission is to promote the values contained in the Texas Lawyers\u2019 Creed of Professionalism.<ref name=\"About Us\">>{{cite web |url= http://www.legalethicstexas.com/About-Us.aspx |title= About Us |publisher= Texas Center for Legal Ethics |accessdate= July 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, at age ninety-eight, he wrote a memoir called ''My Little United Nations: A Team Approach to Growing Older and Wiser and Having Fun Along the Way''\u2014 an account of staying physically and emotionally healthy, despite increasing age and the death of his wife in 2004, with the help of a diverse team of caregivers from around the world.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.texascourthistory.org/documents/TSCHS_JournalWinter2011.pdf |title= Judge Jack Pope Pens Book |year= Winter 2011 |work= Journal of the Texas Supreme Court Historical Society |page= 23 |accessdate= May 14, 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130124072220/http://www.texascourthistory.org/documents/TSCHS_JournalWinter2011.pdf |archive-date= January 24, 2013 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\nOn May 28, 2013,<ref name=\"Access to Justice\">{{cite web |url= http://www.teajf.org/news/releases/2013Session.aspxGovernor |title= Texas Legislature Provides Funding for the State's Legal Aid System \"Chief Justice Jack Pope Act\" to Increase Funds for Civil Legal Aid |date= 28 May 2013 |publisher= Texas Access to Justice Foundation |accessdate= July 1, 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160304033554/http://www.teajf.org/news/releases/2013Session.aspxGovernor |archive-date= 4 March 2016 |url-status= dead }}</ref> Governor [[Rick Perry]] signed into law House Bill 1445, which raised the limit on civil penalties and restitution collected by the Attorney General's Office eligible for supporting legal assistance for the indigent to $50 million per year. The Legislature called the law the Chief Justice Jack Pope Act, in honor of his earlier work championing the [[Interest on Lawyer Trust Accounts|IOLTA]] program which provides legal assistance for the poor. The Act came as a response to shrinking returns under that program.<ref name= \"LegalAid\" />\n\nPope died on 25 February 2017 at the age of 103. He was survived by his two sons, three grandchildren and six great-grandchildren.<ref>[http://www.txcourts.gov/supreme/news/former-chief-justice-jack-pope-1913-2017/ CHIEF JUSTICE JACK POPE, 1913-2017]</ref>\n\nBy the time of his retirement in 1985, Pope had written more than a thousand legal opinions. Upon Pope's passing, Texas Chief Justice [[Nathan Hecht]], a Republican, called him \"a judicial icon. His hard work, scholarship, common sense, humor, and integrity are legendary. No Texas judge has ever been more committed to serving the rule of law and the cause of justice. He was my mentor, role model, counselor, and most especially my friend. Texas has lost a great, great man.\"<ref>\"Former Texas chief justice dies at 103\", ''[[San Antonio Express-News]]'', February 26, 2017, p. A2.</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nIn 2009 he received the TCLE's inaugural Chief Justice Jack Pope Professionalism Award, \"presented annually to both an appellate judge and an appellate lawyer who 'epitomize the highest level of professionalism and integrity.'\"<ref name=\"TCLE\"/> On September 22, 2010 the judicial section of the [[State Bar of Texas]] presented him with its inaugural Judicial Lifetime Achievement Award at its Annual Judicial Conference in Corpus Christi.<ref name= \"BarAward\">{{cite web |url= http://www.judicialsection.com/LifetimeAchievementAward/2010/Chief_Justice_Jack_Pope.pdf |title= First Judicial Lifetime Achievement Award Recipient Chief Justice Jack Pope, Jr. |year= 2013 |work= judicialsection.com |publisher= [[State Bar of Texas]] |accessdate= May 14, 2013 }}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> On April 18, 2013<ref name=\"AustinAmerican\"/> Pope was honored with a ceremony<ref name=\"AustinAmerican\"/> recognizing his 100th birthday in the [[Texas House of Representatives]] within the [[Texas State Capitol]].<ref name=\"AustinAmerican\"/> The House passed a resolution in his honor and \"heard words of praise from four U.S. presidents, as well as the nine U.S. Supreme Court justices.\"<ref name=\"AustinAmerican\">{{cite web |url= http://www.statesman.com/news/news/texas-house-honors-ex-justice-pope-100/nXQXP/|title= Texas House honors ex-Justice Pope, 100 | date=18 April 2013 |work= statesman.com | author=Chuck Lindell | publisher= The Austin-American Statesman |accessdate= July 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pope, Jack}}\n[[Category:1913 births]]\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:Abilene Christian University alumni]]\n[[Category:American centenarians]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Chief Justices of the Texas Supreme Court]]\n[[Category:Texas lawyers]]\n[[Category:People from Abilene, Texas]]\n[[Category:United States Navy reservists]]\n[[Category:University of Texas School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Texas]]\n[[Category:Texas Democrats]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American judge}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|image=Jack Pope in home library, 2011 (cropped).jpg\n|caption= Retired Texas Chief Justice Jack Pope, aged 97, in his home library, March 2011\n|order=\n|office= [[Texas Supreme Court#Chief Justice, Place 1|23rd Texas Supreme Court Justice, <br/> Chief Justice]]\n|term_start=November 29, 1982\n|term_end= January 4, 1985\n|predecessor=[[Joe R. Greenhill]]\n|successor=[[John Hill (Texas politician)|John Hill]]\n|order2=\n|office2=[[Texas Supreme Court]] Associate Justice, Place 2\n|term_start2=January 4, 1965\n|term_end2=November 29, 1982\n|order3=\n|office3=4th Court of Civil Appeals, Justice\n|term_start3=September 12, 1951\n|term_end3=1964\n|order4=\n|office4=94th District Court, District Judge\n|term_start4= December 16, 1946\n|term_end4=1951\n|party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|birth_name=Andrew Jackson Pope Jr.\n|birth_date={{birth date|1913|4|18}}\n|birth_place=[[Abilene, Texas]], U.S.\n|death_date={{death date and age|2017|2|25|1913|4|18}}\n|death_place=[[Austin, Texas]], U.S.\n|resting_place=[[Texas State Cemetery]] <br/> [[Austin, Texas]]\n|spouse=Allene Nichols (d.2004)\n|children=Andrew Jackson Pope III <br/>Walter Allen Pope\n|religion=[[Churches of Christ]]\n|alma_mater=[[University of Texas School of Law]]<br/>[[Abilene Christian University]]\n|profession=[[Lawyer]]\n|allegiance={{flag|United States}}\n|branch={{flag|United States Navy|23px}} <br/> [[United States Naval Reserve]]\n|serviceyears=1944\u20131946\n|battles=[[World War II]]\n}}\n\n'''Andrew Jackson Pope Jr.''', known as '''Jack Pope''' (April 18, 1913 &ndash; February 25, 2017), was an American judge, attorney, author and legal scholar who served as Chief Justice of the [[Supreme Court of Texas]].\n\nPope holds the record of the longest sitting justice in Texas Supreme Court history, having served for 38 years.<ref name= \"Lawbook\" /> At the time of his [[centenarian|100th birthday]], he was the oldest living former Chief Justice of any supreme court in the United States, as well as the longest living chief justice of any supreme court of any state in [[United States]] history.<ref name= \"Lawbook\" >{{cite web |url= http://www.supreme.courts.state.tx.us/pdf/Jackpope100Reprint.pdf |title= Chief Justice Pope Turns 100 |date= April 18, 2013 |work= The Texas Lawbook |publisher= The Supreme Court of Texas |accessdate= May 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nPope was born in [[Abilene, Texas]] <ref name= \"HouseRes\"/> to Dr. Andrew Jackson Pope Sr., a physician, and Ruth Adelia Taylor, a native of [[Nebraska]].<ref name=\"UTBio\">{{cite web |url= http://www.laits.utexas.edu/txp_media/html/just/justices/14.html |title= Pope, Andrew J. | year=2006 | publisher= The University of Texas at Austin|accessdate= July 2, 2013}}</ref> He is a descendant of Andrew Jackson Berry, who fought at the [[Battle of San Jacinto]] in the [[Texas Revolution]].<ref name= \"AltoHerald\"/> After completing high school in Abilene in 1930,<ref name= \"HouseRes\" /> he earned a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree<ref name= \"HouseRes\"/> from Abilene Christian College (now [[Abilene Christian University]])<ref name= \"HouseRes\" /> in 1934, where he had served as Students' Association President.<ref name=\"ACU Today\"/> Pope then served as a student editor of the ''[[Texas Law Review]]'' at the [[University of Texas School of Law]], graduating with a [[Bachelor of Laws]] degree and in 1937 was licensed by the bar.<ref name= \"HouseRes\" /> In 1938, he married Allene Nichols, an elementary school teacher and graduate of the University of Texas whom he met while attending law school;<ref name=\"UTBio\"/> the couple had two sons.<ref name=\"AlleneObit\">{{cite web |url= http://www.christianchronicle.org/article1850458~Obituary%3A_Allene_Nichols_Pope |title= Obituary: Allene Nichols Pope |date=May 2004 |publisher= Christian Chronicle |accessdate= July 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Early legal career ===\nAfter obtaining his license to practice law in Texas in 1937,<ref name= \"HouseRes\"/> Pope \"joined his uncle, former state representative [[Walter Elmer Pope|Walter E. Pope]],\"<ref name= \"HouseRes\"/> at his law firm in [[Corpus Christi, Texas|Corpus Christi]].<ref name= \"HouseRes\"/> His practice consisted of both civil and criminal matters,<ref name= \"HouseRes\"/> such as creditors' rights, oil and gas, personal injury, and family law.<ref name=\"UTBio\"/>\n\nHe went on to manage his uncle's business, the Highway Transportation Company, a passenger \"bus line which operated between Houston, Corpus Christi, and San Antonio.\"<ref name=\"AltoHerald\"/> During this time, he was engaged in the legal interpretation of the new transportation regulatory laws, as well as [[New Deal]] labor laws.<ref name= \"HouseRes\" >{{cite web |url= ftp://ftp.legis.state.tx.us/bills/83R/billtext/html/house_resolutions/HR00800_HR00899/HR00891I.htm |title= House Resolution No. 891 |year= 2013 |publisher= Texas House of Representatives |location= Austin, Texas |accessdate= May 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\nWhen the United States entered [[World War II]], Pope joined the [[United States Navy Reserve|Naval Reserve]] in 1944.<ref name= \"HouseRes\" /> He served on the legal staff of the [[Naval Air Station Corpus Christi|Naval Air Training Station]] in [[Corpus Christi, Texas|Corpus Christi]], as well as on stations in [[Washington, D.C.]] and [[Naval Air Station North Island|San Diego]],<ref name=\"UTBio\"/> until his discharge in 1946.<ref name= \"HouseRes\" />\n\n=== Judge and legal scholar ===\n\n==== District Judge ====\nIn late 1946 Pope was appointed by [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[governor of Texas|Governor]] [[Coke R. Stevenson]] to fill the unexpired term of Judge Allen Wood of the 94th District Court.<ref name=\"AltoHerald\">{{cite web |url= http://texashistory.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metapth215807/m1/3/?q=jack pope | title= Judge Jack Pope Announces for Supreme Court |date=December 1963 |publisher= The Alto Herald|location= Alto, Texas |accessdate= July 1, 2013}}</ref> \nGovernor Stevenson's successor, [[Beauford H. Jester]], then appointed Pope to Judge Wood's four-year term, which began January 1, 1947.<ref name=\"UTBio\"/>\n\nHe became Texas' youngest district judge at the time when he sat on the bench at 33 years of age.<ref name= \"HouseRes\" /> During his time on the district court bench, Pope began writing for and lecturing at legal institutes and before bar associations across [[South Texas]]. His concerns included legal ethics, trial administration, best practices for presenting and excluding evidence, and the Texas [[Jury trial|jury system]]. On several occasions he was appointed to other regional courts to assist when another judge was recused from presiding.<ref name=\"UTBio\"/>\n\n==== Court of Appeals Justice ====\nIn 1950 the Nueces County [[Bar association|Bar Association]] prepared a resolution urging him to campaign for the [[Texas Courts of Appeals|4th Court of Civil Appeals]] in [[San Antonio, Texas|San Antonio]].<ref name=\"UTBio\"/>  Since 1892, of the fifteen judges who had served on that court, all but five had come from San Antonio.<ref name=\"UTBio\"/>  The legal community of [[Nueces County, Texas|Nueces County]] and the [[Rio Grande Valley]] counties hoped to change that trend by nominating and actively campaigning for the young judge.,<ref name=\"UTBio\"/><ref name=\"ACU Today\"/> After winning the primary in July, Pope was appointed to the 4th Court of Appeals' bench by Governor [[Allan Shivers]] to replace Justice Lorenz Broeter, who had resigned.<ref name=\"UTBio\"/>  Pope sat on the court until 1950, whereupon he began serving his own six-year term, with voters subsequently re-electing him to an additional two terms, for a total of 14 years.,<ref name=\"UTBio\"/><ref name=AltoHerald/> In 1961 Pope's judicial review of water rights derived from Spanish and Mexican [[land grant]]s <ref name= \"Lawbook\" /> in the case ''State v. Valmont Plantations'' set a legal precedent which would thereafter set the standard for the adjudication of Texas [[Water law in the United States|water law]].<ref name= \"HouseRes\" /><ref name=\"UTBio\"/><ref name=\"Water Law\">{{cite web |url= http://www.tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/gyw01 | author=Otis W. Templer | title= Water Law |publisher= Texas State Historical Association |accessdate= July 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==== Supreme Court Justice ====\nIn December 1963, Pope declared his intention to run for a vacancy position on the Texas Supreme Court, after receiving 80 petitions from 55 Texas counties with over 2,000 signatures of attorneys pledging their support,<ref name=AltoHerald/> and in 1964 he was elected an [[Associate Justice|associate justice]].<ref name= \"HouseRes\" /> During his tenure as an associate justice, he spearheaded an initiative with the [[State Bar of Texas]] to institute a program for continuing statewide judicial education, and to develop judicial ethics rules. His efforts resulted in both compulsory continuing judicial education and the Court's adoption of The Texas Code of Judicial Conduct in 1974.<ref name= \"Ethicist\" >{{cite web |url= http://www.legalethicstexas.com/Spotlight-on-Ethics/The-Ethicists/Justice-Jack-Pope.aspx |title= Chief Justice Jack Pope |year= 2013 |publisher= Texas Center for Legal Ethics |accessdate= May 14, 2013}}</ref> He was also directly involved in the creation of the Texas State Law Library in 1971, and served on the Friends of the State Law Library Board of Directors.<ref name= \"HouseRes\" />\n\n==== Supreme Court Chief Justice ====\nWhen [[Joe R. Greenhill]] resigned as Chief Justice in October 1982, Governor [[William P. Clements]] appointed Pope to succeed Greenhill.<ref name=\"RioGrande Herald\">{{cite web |url= http://texashistory.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metapth194903/m1/11/?q=jack pope |title= Pope Sworn In |date=23 December 1982 |publisher= The Rio Grande Herald |location= Rio Grande City, Texas | accessdate= July 1, 2013}}</ref> As a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], Clements had crossed party lines to appoint Pope, a lifelong Democrat.<ref name=\"Optimist2\">{{cite web |url= http://texashistory.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metapth96041 |title= Senate Announces Delay in Confirming Justice Pope |date=28 January 1983 |publisher= The Optimist |location= Abilene, Texas | accessdate= July 2, 2013}}</ref> However, when Democrat [[Mark White]] was elected governor that November, a group of 14 Democratic legislators in the Texas Senate publicly stated that they would \"bust\"<ref name=\"Optimist2\"/> all lame-duck appointments by the outgoing Republican governor<ref name=\"RioGrande Herald\"/> regardless of qualifications.<ref name=\"Optimist2\"/><ref name=\"Optimist\">{{cite web |url= http://texashistory.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metapth96043/m1/11/?q=\"chief justice\" pope |title= Jack Pope confirmed Chief Justice |date=4 February 1983 |publisher= The Optimist |location= Abilene, Texas | accessdate= July 2, 2013}}</ref> The Democratic senators attempted to negotiate terms to keep true to their statement of blocking all of the Republican's appointments, while also preserving the power of the Chief Justice position for the Democratic party.<ref name= \"Own Man\"/> However, Pope refused to promise a retirement or interim-only judgeship, saying: \"The citizens of Texas do not want their Chief Justice, or any judge, to make a deal to get a job. If he'll make a deal to get a job, he may keep on making deals to keep that job.\"<ref name= \"Own Man\"/> At a news conference in early 1983, Governor White stated that he did not oppose Pope's confirmation; and in February the Senate voted 29\u20132 in approval.<ref name=\"Optimist2\"/><ref name=\"Optimist\"/>\n\nAfter federal cuts to legal-assistance financing in the early 1980s, as Chief Justice he advocated a way for Texas to guarantee income to finance legal assistance for the poor by using pooled trust-account interest. This program, known as [[Interest on Lawyer Trust Accounts]] (IOLTA), is now used in every U.S. state.<ref name=\"LegalAid\">{{cite web |url= http://www.supreme.courts.state.tx.us/pdf/Governorsignslegalaidsupport.pdf |title= House Bill 1445, Raising Attorney General's Contributions to Civil Legal Services, Signed by Governor Perry |date=May 2013 |publisher= Texas Supreme Court |location= Austin, Texas |accessdate= May 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Later life and death ==\n\nUpon his 1985 retirement Pope had written over 700 opinions for the Supreme Court,<ref name=\"Own Man\">{{cite web |url= http://law.duke.edu/sites/default/files/news/hecht2.pdf |title= Supreme Court of Texas Chief Justice Andrew Jackson \"Jack\" Pope, Jr.: \"Always His Own Man\" |author= Hecht, Nathan |authorlink= Nathan Hecht |date=October 2012 |work= The Storied Third Branch |publisher= Center of Judicial Studies |location= [[Duke University School of Law]] |accessdate= May 14, 2013}}</ref> with an additional 500 opinions as a district judge and court of appeals justice.<ref name=\"AltoHerald\"/> Although he had served as a judge for over 38 years, 21 of those years on the Texas Supreme Court, nearing the Court's mandatory retirement age in 1985 Chief Justice Pope wryly commented: \"Just about the time I was getting the hang of being a judge, I had to retire.\"<ref name=\"UTBio\"/><ref name=\"ACU Today\">{{cite web |url= http://blogs.acu.edu/acutoday/2010/10/05/jack-pope-honored-by-texas-bar-association/ |title= Jack Pope honored for lifetime achievements |year= 2010 |work= blogs.acu.edu |publisher= Abilene Christian University |accessdate= July 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1989 [[Abilene Christian University]] established the Jack Pope Fellows Program \"to offer scholarships to ACU students pursuing public service careers.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.acuoptimist.com/2010/09/hailey-honored-with-endowment-fund/ |title= Hailey honored with endowment fund |author= Williamson, Kelsi |date= September 7, 2010 |work= The Optimist |publisher= Abilene Christian University |access-date= May 14, 2013 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20151121054435/http://www.acuoptimist.com/2010/09/hailey-honored-with-endowment-fund/ |archive-date= November 21, 2015 |df=  }}</ref> The interdisciplinary program gives students with \"good minds and character\" public service educational opportunities in and out of the classroom.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.acu.edu/academics/cas/politicalscience/jackpopefellows/index.html |title= Jack Pope Fellows Program |year= 2013 |work= acu.edu |publisher= Abilene Christian University |accessdate= May 14, 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130403091226/http://www.acu.edu/academics/cas/politicalscience/jackpopefellows/index.html |archive-date= April 3, 2013 |url-status= dead }}</ref> Also in 1989, Pope co-founded the non-profit Texas Center for Legal Ethics with other former Chief Justices [[Joe R. Greenhill]] and [[Robert W. Calvert]].<ref name=TCLE>{{cite web |url= http://www.legalethicstexas.com/spotlight-on-ethics/awards/pope-award.aspx |title= Chief Justice Jack Pope Professionalism Award |year= 2013 |publisher= Texas Center for Legal Ethics |accessdate= May 14, 2013}}</ref> Its mission is to promote the values contained in the Texas Lawyers\u2019 Creed of Professionalism.<ref name=\"About Us\">>{{cite web |url= http://www.legalethicstexas.com/About-Us.aspx |title= About Us |publisher= Texas Center for Legal Ethics |accessdate= July 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, at age ninety-eight, he wrote a memoir called ''My Little United Nations: A Team Approach to Growing Older and Wiser and Having Fun Along the Way''\u2014 an account of staying physically and emotionally healthy, despite increasing age and the death of his wife in 2004, with the help of a diverse team of caregivers from around the world.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.texascourthistory.org/documents/TSCHS_JournalWinter2011.pdf |title= Judge Jack Pope Pens Book |year= Winter 2011 |work= Journal of the Texas Supreme Court Historical Society |page= 23 |accessdate= May 14, 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130124072220/http://www.texascourthistory.org/documents/TSCHS_JournalWinter2011.pdf |archive-date= January 24, 2013 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\nOn May 28, 2013,<ref name=\"Access to Justice\">{{cite web |url= http://www.teajf.org/news/releases/2013Session.aspxGovernor |title= Texas Legislature Provides Funding for the State's Legal Aid System \"Chief Justice Jack Pope Act\" to Increase Funds for Civil Legal Aid |date= 28 May 2013 |publisher= Texas Access to Justice Foundation |accessdate= July 1, 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160304033554/http://www.teajf.org/news/releases/2013Session.aspxGovernor |archive-date= 4 March 2016 |url-status= dead }}</ref> Governor [[Rick Perry]] signed into law House Bill 1445, which raised the limit on civil penalties and restitution collected by the Attorney General's Office eligible for supporting legal assistance for the indigent to $50 million per year. The Legislature called the law the Chief Justice Jack Pope Act, in honor of his earlier work championing the [[Interest on Lawyer Trust Accounts|IOLTA]] program which provides legal assistance for the poor. The Act came as a response to shrinking returns under that program.<ref name= \"LegalAid\" />\n\nPope died on 25 February 2017 at the age of 103. He was survived by his two sons, three grandchildren and six great-grandchildren.<ref>[http://www.txcourts.gov/supreme/news/former-chief-justice-jack-pope-1913-2017/ CHIEF JUSTICE JACK POPE, 1913-2017]</ref>\n\nBy the time of his retirement in 1985, Pope had written more than a thousand legal opinions. Upon Pope's passing, Texas Chief Justice [[Nathan Hecht]], a Republican, called him \"a judicial icon. His hard work, scholarship, common sense, humor, and integrity are legendary. No Texas judge has ever been more committed to serving the rule of law and the cause of justice. He was my mentor, role model, counselor, and most especially my friend. Texas has lost a great, great man.\"<ref>\"Former Texas chief justice dies at 103\", ''[[San Antonio Express-News]]'', February 26, 2017, p. A2.</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nIn 2009 he received the TCLE's inaugural Chief Justice Jack Pope Professionalism Award, \"presented annually to both an appellate judge and an appellate lawyer who 'epitomize the highest level of professionalism and integrity.'\"<ref name=\"TCLE\"/> On September 22, 2010 the judicial section of the [[State Bar of Texas]] presented him with its inaugural Judicial Lifetime Achievement Award at its Annual Judicial Conference in Corpus Christi.<ref name= \"BarAward\">{{cite web |url= http://www.judicialsection.com/LifetimeAchievementAward/2010/Chief_Justice_Jack_Pope.pdf |title= First Judicial Lifetime Achievement Award Recipient Chief Justice Jack Pope, Jr. |year= 2013 |work= judicialsection.com |publisher= [[State Bar of Texas]] |accessdate= May 14, 2013 }}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> On April 18, 2013<ref name=\"AustinAmerican\"/> Pope was honored with a ceremony<ref name=\"AustinAmerican\"/> recognizing his 100th birthday in the [[Texas House of Representatives]] within the [[Texas State Capitol]].<ref name=\"AustinAmerican\"/> The House passed a resolution in his honor and \"heard words of praise from four U.S. presidents, as well as the nine U.S. Supreme Court justices.\"<ref name=\"AustinAmerican\">{{cite web |url= http://www.statesman.com/news/news/texas-house-honors-ex-justice-pope-100/nXQXP/|title= Texas House honors ex-Justice Pope, 100 | date=18 April 2013 |work= statesman.com | author=Chuck Lindell | publisher= The Austin-American Statesman |accessdate= July 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pope, Jack}}\n[[Category:1913 births]]\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:Abilene Christian University alumni]]\n[[Category:American centenarians]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Chief Justices of the Texas Supreme Court]]\n[[Category:Texas lawyers]]\n[[Category:People from Abilene, Texas]]\n[[Category:United States Navy reservists]]\n[[Category:University of Texas School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Texas]]\n[[Category:Texas Democrats]]\n", "name_user": "Marge Simpson IV", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jack_Pope"}
{"title_page": "Alizzz", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=October 2014}}{{notability|Music|date=October 2014}}\n}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| birth_name       = Cristian Quirante\n| birth_place      = Espa\u00f1a\n| genre            = [[R'n'B]], pop, rap, [[Jersey club]], [[Electro (music)|electro]]\n| occupation       = Dj, productor\n| years_active     = 2012\u2013present\n| label            = [[Mad Decent]], [[Warner]],\n| associated_acts  = [[C. Tangana]], [[Rosalia]], [[Ryan Hemsworth]], [[Kelly Rowland]], [[Baauer]], [[Djemba]], [[Flume (musician)|Flume]]\n| website          = \n| background       = non_performing_personnel <!-- producer -->\n| image            = https://ep01.epimg.net/elpais/imagenes/2017/08/01/tentaciones/1501603394_330164_1501603905_noticia_normal_recorte1.jpg\n}}\n\n'''Cristian Quirante''' better known by his stage name '''Alizzz''',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2014/03/20/icon/1395312777_012942.html|title=Alizzz, el DJ que descubri\u00f3 la luz|last=ICON|date=20 March 2014|work=El Pa\u00eds|access-date=21 January 2019|language=es|issn=1134-6582}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lavanguardia.com/vida/20181102/452690480228/productor-musical-cree-que-ahora-los-artistas-son-mas-duenos-de-sus-carreras.html|title=Productor musical cree que ahora los artistas son m\u00e1s due\u00f1os de sus carreras|date=2 November 2018|website=La Vanguardia|access-date=21 January 2019}}</ref> is a Spanish recording artist,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://api.discogs.com/artists/3299732|title=Alizzz|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2019-07-04}}</ref> DJ<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.residentadvisor.net/dj/alizzz|title=RA: Alizzz|website=Resident Advisor|access-date=2019-07-04}}</ref> and music producer<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elperiodico.com/es/ocio-y-cultura/20190630/alizzz-steve-lean-entrevista-productores-beatmakers-musicas-urbanas-7526878|title=Alizzz y Steve Lean: los amos del ritmo urbano|last=Fortuny|first=Ignasi|date=2019-06-30|website=elperiodico|language=es|access-date=2019-07-04}}</ref> <ref>{{Citation|title=Reportaje PRODUCCI\u00d3N MUSICAL (con Alizzz y Carlos Narea)|date=2019-10-15|url=http://www.rtve.es/alacarta/videos/la-hora-musa/reportaje-produccion-musical-alizzz-carlos-narea/5410665/|language=es|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref>based in [[Barcelona]]. His sound is influenced by [[R'n'B]], [[Rap]] and Pop.\n\n== Career ==\nAlizzz' career started in 2012 with the release of the single '<nowiki/>'''Neon Lights'''' ('''MofoHifi''',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mofohifi.com/site/2012/04/alizzz-neon-lights/|title=Alizzz \u2013 Neon Lights {{!}} MofoHifi Records|website=www.mofohifi.com|access-date=15 August 2018}}</ref> when he proved his ability to combine bass, maximalist synths and a new wave of samples and rhythm changes.  The single was quickly followed by the ''''Loud EP'''' ('''MofoHifi''', 2012<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://neonized.net/blog/reviews/alizzz-loud-ep/|title=Alizzz \u2013 Loud EP {{!}} Neonized|website=neonized.net|language=es-ES|access-date=15 August 2018}}</ref>) which succeeded in placing him squarely on the international scene.\nIn 2013 he started the year with a new remix for the Spanish label '''Arkestra''' of ''''En otra ciudad'''' by '''TiMOTi''', ''''Collapse EP'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mofohifi.com/site/2013/04/alizzz-collapse-ep/|title=Alizzz \u2013 Collapse EP {{!}} MofoHifi Records|website=www.mofohifi.com|access-date=15 August 2018}}</ref>'''<nowiki/>'''' for MofoHifi Records<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.the-monitors.com/2014/05/22/alizzz-grunge-dubstep-whoa/|title=Alizzz: From Grunge to Dubstep to 'Whoa!' \u2013 The Monitors|date=22 May 2014|work=The Monitors|access-date=15 August 2018}}</ref> and ''''Whoa! EP'''' for '''Arkestra'''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.conceptoradio.net/2013/06/11/escucha-integramente-whoa-el-nuevo-ep-de-alizzz/|title=Escucha \u00edntegramente \"Whoa!\", el nuevo EP de Alizzz|date=11 June 2013|work=Concepto Radio|access-date=15 August 2018|language=es-ES}}</ref>\nAt the end of 2013 he signed to [[Diplo]]'s label [[Mad Decent]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://maddecent.com/artist/alizzz/|title=Mad Decent|website=maddecent.com|access-date=15 August 2018}}</ref> where he released the ''''Sunshine Ep''''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2014/03/20/icon/1395312777_012942.html|title=Alizzz, el DJ que descubri\u00f3 la luz|last=ICON|date=20 March 2014|work=El Pa\u00eds|access-date=15 August 2018|language=es|issn=1134-6582}}</ref> on the labels imprint '''Jeffre's''' and began touring internationally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.residentadvisor.net/dj/alizzz/dates?yr=2018/|title=RA: Alizzz tour dates|last=Advisor|first=Resident|website=Resident Advisor|access-date=15 August 2018}}</ref>\nIn 2015 he released the single ''''Your Love''''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jenesaispop.com/2015/11/16/243527/alizzz-estrena-your-love-con-max-marshall/|title=Alizzz estrena 'Your Love' con Max Marshall \u2013 jenesaispop.com|website=jenesaispop.com|language=es|access-date=15 August 2018}}</ref> on the USA label Moving Castle. \nAlizzz has toured Europe, Japan (2014) and Australia (2015), with follow up EP '''<nowiki/>'Ascension'''' on Moving Castle and his first self release, the hip hop collaboration, '''Ocean Drive'''.\n\n<nowiki/>'''<nowiki/><nowiki/>'''\n\nIn 2016 Alizzz began collaborations with C Tangana<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tiumag.com/news/alizzz-productor-pill-up-on-me-ctangana/|title=Alizzz est\u00e1 movi\u00e9ndose en terreno virgen \u2013 TIU {{!}} Future Music|date=4 July 2017|work=TIU {{!}} Future Music|access-date=15 August 2018|language=es-ES}}</ref> and [[Rosal\u00eda (singer)|Rosalia]], writing and recording \"Antes de Morirme<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://cadenaser.com/programa/2017/12/18/fuego_y_chinchetas/1513609395_318270.html|title=Alizzz: el genio oculto tras C. Tangana|last=Cano|first=Carlos G.|date=2017-12-18|work=Cadena SER|access-date=2018-08-15|language=es-ES}}</ref>\" and \u2018Ll\u00e1mame m\u00e1s tarde<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vice.com/es/article/vdkzw3/r-n-b-espana-noisey-2907|title=Conoce a los j\u00f3venes talentos de la escena R&B espa\u00f1ola|date=29 July 2016|work=Vice|access-date=15 August 2018|language=es}}</ref>\u2019.   From here the collaboration continued to encompass C Tangana's debut album \u00cdDOLO,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/albums/C-tangana/Idolo|title=\u00cddolo by C. Tangana|website=Genius|access-date=15 August 2018}}</ref> for which production and recordings were made between September 2016 and June 2017.   In June 2017 Mala Mujer was released and received 3xPlatinum in Spain.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2017/12/15/tentaciones/1513330167_980671.html|title=C. Tangana consigue el doble disco de platino por su canci\u00f3n 'Mala Mujer'|last=20Minutos|work=20minutos.es \u2013 \u00daltimas Noticias|access-date=15 August 2018|language=es}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018 Alizzz headlined Barcelona Sonar festival's 25yr addition.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://sonar.es/es/2018/artistas/alizzz|title=Alizzz \u2013 S\u00f3nar Barcelona 2018|work=S\u00f3nar Barcelona|access-date=15 August 2018|language=es}}</ref>   To date Alizzz has achieved a total of 15 platinum certified recordings internationally.\n\n== Record label ==\nIn January 2019 Alizzz launched a record label in partnership with Warner Records Spain, called Whoa! Music,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8494972/alizzz-warner-music-spain-whoa-label-launch|title=Alizzz Partners With Warner Music Spain on 'Whoa' Label|website=Billboard|access-date=1 February 2019}}</ref> the concept of the label being to develop and release avant garde Spanish and Latin American artists, artists on the label include Alizzz,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/es/article/eved7p/jesse-baez-y-paula-cendejas-encienden-tus-dms-en-tu-cama|title=Jesse B\u00e1ez y Paula Cendejas encienden tus DMs en \"Tu cama\"|last=Cope|first=Cristian|last2=Ram\u00edrez|first2=Sebasti\u00e1n L\u00f3pez|date=2019-01-25|website=Noisey|language=es|access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref> Paula Cendejas,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://los40.com/los40/2019/03/07/musica/1551981272_839032.html|title=Paula Cendejas va a ser la sensaci\u00f3n del pop espa\u00f1ol y el productor de C. Tangana lo sabe bien|last=LOS40|date=2019-03-11|website=LOS40|language=es|access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref> Coral Casino<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/es/article/xwbbya/coral-casino-tambien-sabe-que-las-relaciones-son-un-maldito-rally|title=Coral Casino tambi\u00e9n sabe que las relaciones son un maldito \"Rally\"|last=Rios|first=Juan Carlos|date=2019-03-29|website=Noisey|language=es|access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref> and Robie<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://highxtar.com/robie-the-new-promise-of-urban-music-presents-que-sera/?lang=en|title=Robie, the new promise of new pop music, presents \"\u00bfQu\u00e9 ser\u00e1?\"|date=2019-07-04|website=HIGHXTAR.|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-04}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Title\n!Year\n!Album / EP\n!Label\n|-\n|Neon Lights\n|2012\n|Neon Lights\n|MofoHifi Records\n|-\n|Loud\n|2012\n| rowspan=\"4\" |Loud EP\n| rowspan=\"4\" |MofoHifi Records\n|-\n|Cruel\n|2012\n|-\n|Tactel\n|2012\n|-\n|Loud \u2013 The Young Punx Mix\n|2012\n|-\n|Whoa!\n|2013\n| rowspan=\"4\" |Whoa! EP\n| rowspan=\"4\" |Arkestra Discos\n|-\n|Champagne \u2013 Featuring Congo Lacosta\n|2013\n|-\n|In Chains\n|2013\n|-\n|Turquoise\n|2013\n|-\n|Collapse \u2013 Featuring Dreamon\n|2014\n|Collapse \n|MofoHifi Records\n|-\n|Sunshine\n|2014\n| rowspan=\"4\" |Sunshine EP\n| rowspan=\"4\" |Mad Decent\n|-\n|I C U\n|2014\n|-\n|That Gurl\n|2014\n|-\n|What IF\n|2014\n|-\n|Your Love Featuring Max Marshall\n|2015\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Your Love EP\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Moving Castle Records\n|-\n|Basic C